### Host Discovery
```bash
nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24

## Basic Port Scan
------------------
nmap 192.168.1.10

## Service Version Detection
-----------------
nmap -sV 192.168.1.10

## Aggressive Scan
----------------
nmap -A 192.168.1.10

## Full TCP Port Scan
-------------------
nmap -p- 192.168.1.10

## Explanation

I started with host discovery to identify active systems in the network range. After finding a live host, I performed a basic Nmap scan to check for open ports. I then used version detection and aggressive scanning to gather more details about services running on the target.

This process helped me understand how exposed services can become part of an organization’s attack surface.

## Sample Findings

Port 22 open — SSH

Port 80 open — HTTP

Port 443 open — HTTPS

## Detected service versions on open ports

Confirmed that multiple services were externally reachable in the lab

## Security Observation

Open ports and exposed services increase attack surface. Even when a service is legitimate, it should be reviewed to confirm whether it is necessary, securely configured, and properly patched.

## Recommendation

Close unused ports

Limit unnecessary public exposure

Update vulnerable services

Monitor externally facing systems regularly

Perform periodic scanning as part of security hygiene

## Outcome

This lab improved my understanding of reconnaissance, port enumeration, and how to present technical findings in a clear analyst-style format.

